          "text": "     1→export interface BlogPost {\n     2→  id: string;\n     3→  title: string;\n     4→  excerpt: string;\n     5→  content: string;\n     6→  date: string;\n     7→  readTime: string;\n     8→  tags: string[];\n     9→  slug: string;\n    10→}\n    11→\n    12→export const blogPosts: BlogPost[] = [\n    13→  {\n    14→    id: \"1\",\n    15→    title: \".NET 9 Telemetry: pushing logs and metrics to HELK with OpenTelemetry\",\n    16→    excerpt: \"Modern observability: sending .NET 9 telemetry to HELK with OpenTelemetry for logs, traces, and metrics.\",\n    17→    content: `# .NET 9 Telemetry: pushing logs and metrics to HELK with OpenTelemetry\n    18→\n    19→*14 Nov 2024 — Mind of a Coder*\n    20→*Exploring the intersection of software development, engineering best practices, and artificial intelligence. Deep dives into code, architecture, and the future of tech.*\n    21→\n    22→> Modern observability: sending .NET 9 telemetry to HELK with OpenTelemetry for logs, traces, and metrics.\n    23→\n    24→---\n    25→\n    26→## The problem\n    27→\n    28→You've got a .NET 9 service and a HELK stack (Elasticsearch + Logstash + Kibana, often with Kafka) powering threat hunting and analytics. You want **one instrumentation** strategy—OpenTelemetry (OTel)—to ship **logs, traces, and metrics** into HELK without sprinkling per-signal agents everywhere. Keep it simple, vendor-agnostic, and production-grade. HELK is ELK under the hood, so if we can shape OTel data for Elasticsearch/Kibana properly, we're golden. ([GitHub][1])\n    29→\n    30→## The approach (TL;DR)\n    31→\n    32→1. **Instrument .NET 9 with OTel** (logs, metrics, traces) and **export via OTLP** to an **OpenTelemetry Collector**.\n    33→2. In the **Collector**, use the **Elasticsearch exporter** to send all three signals to HELK's Elasticsearch in **OTel-native mapping** (or ECS if you prefer classic Kibana dashboards). Recent Elastic docs confirm logs, metrics, and traces are supported. ([Elastic][2])\n    34→3. (Optional) If you want the Elastic APM UI for deep traces, add **APM Server** and send OTLP there; it natively accepts OTLP/HTTP and OTLP/gRPC. ([Elastic][3])\n    35→\n    36→This keeps your app clean (one exporter), makes the Collector your \"router/transformer,\" and lands data in HELK ready to query/visualize.\n    37→\n    38→---\n    39→\n    40→## Wiring up .NET 9 (one-time setup)\n    41→\n    42→**Packages** (csproj – versions omitted on purpose; use the latest stable):\n    43→\n    44→\\`\\`\\`xml\n    45→<ItemGroup>\n    46→  <PackageReference Include=\"OpenTelemetry.Extensions.Hosting\" />\n    47→  <PackageReference Include=\"OpenTelemetry.Exporter.OpenTelemetryProtocol\" />\n    48→  <PackageReference Include=\"OpenTelemetry.Instrumentation.AspNetCore\" />\n    49→  <PackageReference Include=\"OpenTelemetry.Instrumentation.Http\" />\n    50→  <PackageReference Include=\"OpenTelemetry.Instrumentation.Runtime\" />\n    51→  <PackageReference Include=\"OpenTelemetry.Logs\" />\n    52→</ItemGroup>\n    53→\\`\\`\\`\n    54→\n    55→**Program.cs** (minimal API):\n    56→\n    57→\\`\\`\\`csharp\n    58→using OpenTelemetry.Resources;\n    59→using OpenTelemetry.Trace;\n    60→using OpenTelemetry.Metrics;\n    61→\n    62→var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);\n    63→\n    64→// ship logs via OTLP to the Collector\n    65→builder.Logging.ClearProviders();\n    66→builder.Logging.AddOpenTelemetry(o =>\n    67→{\n    68→    o.IncludeFormattedMessage = true;\n    69→    o.IncludeScopes = true;\n    70→    o.ParseStateValues = true;\n    71→    o.AddOtlpExporter(); // default http://localhost:4318\n    72→});\n    73→\n    74→// single OTel setup for traces & metrics\n    75→builder.Services.AddOpenTelemetry()\n    76→    .ConfigureResource(r => r\n    77→        .AddService(serviceName: \"crm.api\", serviceVersion: \"1.0.0\")\n    78→        .AddAttributes(new KeyValuePair<string, object>[] {\n    79→            new(\"deployment.environment\", Environment.GetEnvironmentVariable(\"ENV\") ?? \"dev\")\n    80→        }))\n    81→    .WithTracing(t => t\n    82→        .AddAspNetCoreInstrumentation()\n    83→        .AddHttpClientInstrumentation()\n    84→        .AddSource(\"crm.api\")           // your ActivitySource if you do manual spans\n    85→        .AddOtlpExporter())\n    86→    .WithMetrics(m => m\n    87→        .AddAspNetCoreInstrumentation()\n    88→        .AddHttpClientInstrumentation()\n    89→        .AddRuntimeInstrumentation()\n    90→        .AddProcessInstrumentation()\n    91→        .AddOtlpExporter());\n    92→\n    93→var app = builder.Build();\n    94→app.MapGet(\"/health\", () => \"ok\");\n    95→app.Run();\n    96→\\`\\`\\`\n    97→\n    98→> Why OTLP? It's the native OTel protocol, widely supported by collectors/backends and avoids lossy translations. ([OpenTelemetry][4])\n    99→\n   100→---\n   101→\n   102→## OpenTelemetry Collector → HELK (Elasticsearch)\n   103→\n   104→### Option A — **Direct to Elasticsearch** (simple, fast)\n   105→\n   106→Use the **Elasticsearch exporter** in the Collector and pick a mapping:\n   107→\n   108→* \\`mapping.mode: otel\\` → OTel-native schema (great for consistency across tools)\n   109→* \\`mapping.mode: ecs\\` → Elastic Common Schema (handy if you've got existing ECS dashboards)\n   110→\n   111→Elastic's current docs state the exporter supports logs, metrics, and traces. ([Elastic][2])\n   112→\n   113→**collector.yaml**\n   114→\n   115→\\`\\`\\`yaml\n   116→receivers:\n   117→  otlp:\n   118→    protocols:\n   119→      http:\n   120→      grpc\n   121→\n   122→processors:\n   123→  batch:\n   124→  resource:\n   125→    attributes:\n   126→      - key: env\n   127→        action: upsert\n   128→        value: \\${ENVIRONMENT}\n   129→\n   130→exporters:\n   131→  elasticsearch:\n   132→    # point to HELK's Elasticsearch\n   133→    endpoints: [\"https://helk-es:9200\"]\n   134→    user: elastic\n   135→    password: \\${ELASTIC_PASSWORD}\n   136→    # or: api_key: \\${ELASTIC_API_KEY}\n   137→    mapping:\n   138→      mode: otel    # or \"ecs\" if you want ECS fields\n   139→\n   140→service:\n   141→  pipelines:\n   142→    logs:\n   143→      receivers: [otlp]\n   144→      processors: [resource, batch]\n   145→      exporters: [elasticsearch]\n   146→    metrics:\n   147→      receivers: [otlp]\n   148→      processors: [resource, batch]\n   149→      exporters: [elasticsearch]\n   150→    traces:\n   151→      receivers: [otlp]\n   152→      processors: [resource, batch]\n   153→      exporters: [elasticsearch]\n   154→\\`\\`\\`\n   155→\n   156→### Option B — **Use Elastic APM Server** (for the APM UI)\n   157→\n   158→If your HELK includes **APM Server** (or you add it), send traces/metrics over OTLP to APM; logs can still go straight to Elasticsearch. APM Server natively speaks OTLP over HTTP and gRPC. ([Elastic][3])\n   159→\n   160→\\`\\`\\`yaml\n   161→exporters:\n   162→  otlphttp/apm:\n   163→    endpoint: http://apm-server:8200\n   164→    # headers: { Authorization: \"Bearer <token>\" } # if needed\n   165→  elasticsearch:\n   166→    endpoints: [\"https://helk-es:9200\"]\n   167→    user: elastic\n   168→    password: \\${ELASTIC_PASSWORD}\n   169→    mapping:\n   170→      mode: otel\n   171→\n   172→service:\n   173→  pipelines:\n   174→    traces:\n   175→      receivers: [otlp]\n   176→      processors: [batch]\n   177→      exporters: [otlphttp/apm]\n   178→    metrics:\n   179→      receivers: [otlp]\n   180→      processors: [batch]\n   181→      exporters: [otlphttp/apm]\n   182→    logs:\n   183→      receivers: [otlp]\n   184→      processors: [batch]\n   185→      exporters: [elasticsearch]\n   186→\\`\\`\\`\n   187→\n   188→### Option C — **Kafka + Logstash** (when HELK standardizes on Kafka)\n   189→\n   190→HELK often rides with Kafka/Logstash. You can fan out via Kafka and keep Logstash pipelines you already have. ([thehelk.com][5])\n   191→\n   192→**collector.yaml (logs via Kafka)**\n   193→\n   194→\\`\\`\\`yaml\n   195→exporters:\n   196→  kafka:\n   197→    brokers: [\"kafka:9092\"]\n   198→    topic: otel-logs\n   199→    encoding: otlp_json\n   200→\n   201→service:\n   202→  pipelines:\n   203→    logs:\n   204→      receivers: [otlp]\n   205→      processors: [batch]\n   206→      exporters: [kafka]\n   207→\\`\\`\\`\n   208→\n   209→**logstash.conf**\n   210→\n   211→\\`\\`\\`conf\n   212→input {\n   213→  kafka {\n   214→    bootstrap_servers => \"kafka:9092\"\n   215→    topics => [\"otel-logs\"]\n   216→    codec => json\n   217→  }\n   218→}\n   219→\n   220→# optional transforms here (mutate/grok)\n   221→output {\n   222→  elasticsearch {\n   223→    hosts => [\"http://helk-es:9200\"]\n   224→    index => \"otel-logs-%{+YYYY.MM.dd}\"\n   225→  }\n   226→}\n   227→\\`\\`\\`\n   228→\n   229→---\n   230→\n   231→## Querying in Kibana\n   232→\n   233→* With **\\`mapping.mode: otel\\`**, your docs use OTel-native field names; use **Discover** and build Lens/Alerts directly.\n   234→* With **\\`mapping.mode: ecs\\`**, your logs fit classic ECS visualizations and SIEM/hunting content more naturally.\n   235→* If you installed **APM Server**, use the **APM app** for traces/service maps; Elasticsearch stores the data underneath. ([Elastic][2])\n   236→\n   237→---\n   238→\n   239→## Alternatives (and why I didn't pick them)\n   240→\n   241→* **Ship app logs via Filebeat/Elastic Agent only**: fine for logs, but then you still need a story for traces/metrics; OTel keeps all three signals consistent and correlatable. ([OpenTelemetry][6])\n   242→* **Send straight from .NET to Elasticsearch**: possible via community libs, but you lose the Collector's routing, batching, retries, and signal-wise policies. The Collector is the control plane. ([OpenTelemetry][7])\n   243→* **Grafana stack (Loki/Tempo/Mimir)**: great stack, but if HELK is your center of gravity and your hunters live in Kibana, Elasticsearch-first keeps the operational surface smaller.\n   244→\n   245→---\n   246→\n   247→## Gotchas & notes from the trenches\n   248→\n   249→* **Indices & privileges**: ensure the exporter's credential can create/write indices (mapping conflicts bite). Monitor exporter failure metrics and Collector logs during rollout. ([GitHub][8])\n   250→* **Choose your mapping early**: flipping between \\`ecs\\` and \\`otel\\` later means reindexing or dual-write during migration. ([Elastic][2])\n   251→* **APM or not?** If you want native APM views, add **APM Server**. If not, you can still visualize traces in Kibana via Discover/Visualize, but you'll miss curated APM UX. ([Elastic][3])\n   252→\n   253→---\n   254→\n   255→## Final checklist\n   256→\n   257→* [ ] .NET 9 app emits logs/metrics/traces via OTLP. ([Microsoft Learn][9])\n   258→* [ ] Collector receives OTLP(\\`4317\\` gRPC, \\`4318\\` HTTP) and batches. ([OpenTelemetry][10])\n   259→* [ ] Exporter: **Elasticsearch** (mapping \\`otel\\` or \\`ecs\\`) **or** **APM Server** for traces/metrics. ([Elastic][2])\n   260→* [ ] Kibana dashboards wired; (optional) APM UI if using APM Server. ([Elastic][11])\n   261→\n   262→---\n   263→\n   264→## Appendix: minimal manual span (optional)\n   265→\n   266→\\`\\`\\`csharp\n   267→using System.Diagnostics;\n   268→\n   269→var source = new ActivitySource(\"crm.api\");\n   270→\n   271→app.MapGet(\"/work\", () =>\n   272→{\n   273→    using var activity = source.StartActivity(\"heavy-work\");\n   274→    // ... your code\n   275→    return Results.Ok(new { ok = true });\n   276→});\n   277→\\`\\`\\`\n   278→\n   279→---\n   280→\n   281→### References\n   282→\n   283→* HELK introduces an ELK-based hunting platform with analytics (Spark/GraphFrames/Jupyter). ([thehelk.com][5])\n   284→* Elastic Stack **APM Server** supports **OTLP** (HTTP & gRPC). ([Elastic][3])\n   285→* **Elasticsearch exporter** in the OTel Collector supports **logs, metrics, traces** and multiple mapping modes (including \\`otel\\` and \\`ecs\\`). ([Elastic][2])\n   286→* .NET observability with OpenTelemetry (official docs). ([Microsoft Learn][9])\n   287→\n   288→\n   289→[1]: https://github.com/cyb3rward0g/helk/wiki?utm_source=chatgpt.com \"Home · Cyb3rWard0g/HELK Wiki\"\n   290→[2]: https://www.elastic.co/docs/reference/opentelemetry/edot-collector/components/elasticsearchexporter?utm_source=chatgpt.com \"Elasticsearch exporter | Elastic Agent release notes\"\n   291→[3]: https://www.elastic.co/docs/solutions/observability/apm/opentelemetry-intake-api?utm_source=chatgpt.com \"OpenTelemetry intake API | Elastic Docs\"\n   292→[4]: https://opentelemetry.io/docs/languages/js/exporters/?utm_source=chatgpt.com \"Exporters\"\n   293→[5]: https://thehelk.com/intro.html?utm_source=chatgpt.com \"Introduction — The HELK\"\n   294→[6]: https://opentelemetry.io/docs/specs/otel/logs/?utm_source=chatgpt.com \"OpenTelemetry Logging\"\n   295→[7]: https://opentelemetry.io/docs/collector/?utm_source=chatgpt.com \"Collector\"\n   296→[8]: https://github.com/open-telemetry/opentelemetry-collector-contrib/issues/32302?utm_source=chatgpt.com \"[exporter/elasticsearchexporter] Push failures not reported ...\"\n   297→[9]: https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/diagnostics/observability-with-otel?utm_source=chatgpt.com \"NET Observability with OpenTelemetry\"\n   298→[10]: https://opentelemetry.io/docs/collector/configuration/?utm_source=chatgpt.com \"Configuration\"\n   299→[11]: https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/observability/8.19/apm-open-telemetry.html?utm_source=chatgpt.com \"Use OpenTelemetry with APM | Elastic Observability [8.19]\"`,\n   300→    date: \"2024-11-14\",\n   301→    readTime: \"12 min read\",\n   302→    tags: [\"dotnet\", \"opentelemetry\", \"observability\", \"helk\", \"elasticsearch\"],\n   303→    slug: \"dotnet-9-telemetry-helk-opentelemetry\"\n   304→  }\n   305→];\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether 