        {
          "type": "user",
          "text": "aggiungi questo articolo datato 15 luglio 2025.\nti passo il markdown, se vuoi puoi svilupparlo e correggerlo.\n---\ntitle: \"A New Way of Working: AI, Code Quality, Testing, and Documentation\"\ndate: 2025-02-27\nsubtitle: \"Reducing cognitive load without sacrificing ownership\"\n---\n\n# A New Way of Working: AI, Code Quality, Testing, and Documentation\n\nFor years we pretended that productivity was about writing more code, faster.  \nThat illusion is finally collapsing under its own weight.\n\nModern engineering teams don’t fail because they can’t ship features.  \nThey fail because they ship **entropy**: unreviewed code, fragile logic, tribal knowledge, and documentation that lies the moment it’s written.\n\nThis “new way of working” didn’t start as a manifesto.  \nIt emerged as a survival mechanism.\n\n---\n\n## The Real Problem We Were Solving\n\nThe core issue wasn’t velocity.  \nIt was **cognitive overload**.\n\n- Codebases grow faster than shared understanding  \n- Reviews degrade into “LGTM”  \n- Tests exist but aren’t trusted  \n- Documentation is missing or obsolete  \n- AI tools are used randomly, without ownership  \n\nThe result is predictable: senior engineers become bottlenecks, juniors hesitate, and the system becomes harder to change every month.\n\nThe goal is simple to state and hard to execute:\n\n> **Reduce cognitive load while increasing code confidence.**\n\nAI is a lever. Not the solution.\n\n---\n\n## AI as a Force Multiplier, Not a Decision Maker\n\nThe biggest mistake teams make with AI is treating it like a junior developer you can delegate work to.\n\nThat’s backwards.\n\nAI is closer to a **hyper-fast intern with infinite memory and zero accountability**.\n\nSo we redesigned the workflow around one non-negotiable rule:\n\n> **AI can generate, suggest, refactor — but never own decisions.**\n\nIn practice:\n\n- AI writes the **first draft**, never the final one  \n- AI proposes tests, not testing strategy  \n- AI explains code, humans validate correctness  \n- AI accelerates feedback loops, not architectural choices  \n\nThis framing removes fear and restores ownership.\n\n---\n\n## Code Quality Starts Before Code Exists\n\nTraditional pipelines treat quality as a downstream concern:\n\n```text\nwrite code → review → test → fix\n```\n\nThat’s inefficient.\n\nWe shifted quality **left**, before implementation.\n\n### AI-Assisted Design Sketching\n\nBefore writing production code, we ask AI to:\n\n- Outline data models  \n- Sketch function signatures  \n- Identify edge cases  \n- Propose failure modes  \n\nNot to accept them blindly, but to **force early thinking**.\n\n```text\nPrompt:\n\"Given this requirement, list invariants, edge cases,\nand failure scenarios. Assume high scale and partial failure.\"\n```\n\nBy the time code is written, most conceptual bugs are already exposed.\n\n---\n\n## Code Reviews: From Gatekeeping to Reasoning\n\nAI didn’t reduce the importance of code reviews.  \nIt made **bad reviews unacceptable**.\n\nWe changed the review contract:\n\n- Reviews are about **reasoning**, not syntax  \n- Every non-trivial PR must explain *why*, not just *what*  \n- AI-generated code must be explicitly acknowledged  \n\nA good PR description answers:\n\n- What problem does this solve?  \n- Why this approach?  \n- What alternatives were rejected?  \n- What breaks if this changes?  \n\nAI helps reviewers by summarizing diffs and highlighting risk areas.  \nHumans decide if the logic stands.\n\n---\n\n## Testing Is Not Optional (But It’s Not Sacred Either)\n\nHere’s the uncomfortable truth: many teams write tests they don’t trust.\n\nWe stopped pretending otherwise.\n\nTests are now **explicitly layered**:\n\n1. **AI-generated unit tests**  \n   Fast, cheap, good at coverage — weak on intent  \n\n2. **Human-written critical-path tests**  \n   Focused on invariants and business rules  \n\n3. **Contract and integration tests**  \n   Treated as system documentation, not just safety nets  \n\nAI is excellent at producing boilerplate:\n\n```pseudo\nfor each edge_case:\n  given input\n  expect output\n```\n\nHumans decide **which edge cases matter**.\n\n---\n\n## Documentation as a Living Artifact\n\nDocumentation rots because writing it feels like a tax.\n\nAI changes that dynamic.\n\nWe flipped the process:\n\n- Documentation is generated **from code and PRs**  \n- Engineers review docs the same way they review code  \n- Docs are versioned, diffed, and owned  \n\nTypical prompts:\n\n```text\n\"Explain this module as if onboarding a new engineer\"\n\"Summarize this PR in architectural terms\"\n\"What assumptions does this service make?\"\n```\n\nDocumentation stops being an afterthought and becomes a **byproduct of thinking**.\n\n---\n\n## The Cultural Shift (The Hard Part)\n\nTools don’t change teams.  \nExpectations do.\n\nThis way of working only functions if:\n\n- Ownership is non-negotiable  \n- “AI wrote it” is never an excuse  \n- Slower decisions are acceptable under uncertainty  \n- Engineers are evaluated on clarity, not output volume  \n\nAI amplifies both good and bad engineering habits.  \nIf the culture is weak, AI accelerates the collapse.\n\n---\n\n## The Result\n\nThe outcome isn’t magical productivity gains.\n\nIt’s something better:\n\n- Fewer production surprises  \n- Less heroism, more consistency  \n- Code that can be explained, not just executed  \n- Teams that scale without burning seniors  \n\nThis isn’t the future of work.  \nIt’s the correction we should have made years ago.\n\nAnd it’s still a work in progress.\n",
